<DOC><DOCNO> AP881214-0242 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0046EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-NewCable     12-14 0174</FIRST><SECOND>AM-New Cable,0180</SECOND><HEAD>New Trans-Atlantic Cable Will Increase Phone Capacity</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The first fiber-optic telephone cable across theAtlantic goes into service Wednesday, greatly increasing the numberof calls that can be placed to Europe at one time, according to apublished report.   The New York Times, in Wednesday's editions, says the new cablecan carry 40,000 calls simultaneously by using pulses of laser lightto send voice and computer data.   The three existing trans-Atlantic cables, made of copper, alongwith satellites, can carry a total of 20,000 calls, the Times noted.   The new cable was installed over six months at a cost of $362million and illustrates the increasing pace with whichcommunications companies are stringing fiber-optic cables along theocean floor and across North America, Europe, Asia and Australia.   The cable is a joint venture of 29 European and North Americantelephone companies, including American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co.,ITT Corp., British Telecommunications PLC, France Telcom and WesternUnion. ATandamp;T, which installed the cable, will also operate it.</TEXT></DOC>